## Model Training

Models are trained in the conda `tf` environment and exported to ONNX.

### MNIST Classifier
```bash
conda activate tf
cd ~/data/l/python/tf
python mnist.py                    # trains and saves mnist_model/
python convert_to_onnx.py
```

### CVAE Generator
```bash
conda activate tf
cd ~/data/l/python/tf
python train_cvae.py               # trains and saves cvae_generator.h5
python convert_to_onnx.py cvae_generator cvae_generator.onnx
```

python -m tf2onnx.convert --saved-model mnist_model --output mnist_model.onnx
python -m tf2onnx.convert --keras cvae_generator.h5 --output cvae_generator.onnx

python -m tf2onnx.convert --keras cvae_generator.h5 --output cvae_generator.onnx && python test_cvae.py

python convert_generator.py && python test_cvae.py

Architecture:

Different activation functions — Try LeakyReLU, GELU, or Swish instead of ReLU
Residual connections in generator — Skip connections between conv layers
Multi-scale label injection — Inject label at different resolutions (not just spatial tiling)

One-cycle policy — Single cycle of LR increase then decrease
Gradient accumulation — Simulate larger batch sizes with smaller physical batches
Exponential moving average — EMA of generator weights for more stable generation

Regularization: 11. Spectral normalization — Normalize weight matrices instead of activations
Feature matching loss — Match intermediate feature distributions

Perceptual loss — Use VGG features for reconstruction loss
Adversarial loss — Add a discriminator for sharper outputs
KL annealing with free bits — Allow some dimensions to have low KL penalty

Data: 18. Curriculum learning — Start with easy classes, gradually add harder ones 19. Class-balanced sampling — Ensure equal representation of all classes per batch


